,Recommended,294440,11814765,"Posted: 21 August, 2014",all,[AHOP] Armand Vestibule,"Shadowgate hearkens back to the classic point and click adventures from the days of early computer gaming.  You start off with just a nudge out the door, a torch and a dirk and are charged with the quest of vanquishing evil in the living castle of Shadowgate.The game is loaded with puzzles, traps, and head-scratching moments depending on your chosen difficulty.  Having said that, I distinctly remember the NES version being far easier.  Perhaps the hardest difficulty wasn't the best idea...The menu options are pretty much the same as they were, but the full-screen approach to the UI is a nice change away from the classic version.  You get to see far more of the environment and the amount of detail that went into the hand-painted imagery.As I delve further and further into the game, I find some of the puzzles famliar but often with new twists (also thanks to the difficulty).  It's tough, at times, and potentiallly frustrating as all good puzzle games should be.The music is atmospheric and adaptive, laced with familiar nostalgic themes from the classic. The artwork is nice and crisp and the added storyline so far makes it far more immersive than its original form.For exta nostalgia, they have options to utilize some of the classic NES features such as the music and room transitions.I would recommend it to fans of the original and fans of point-and-click adventures (like Myst and its ilk).  Beyond that, if you don't like this genre of game, Shadowgate doesn't really offer anything outside of what's safely within the niche of the genre."
