76561198075673573,Recommended,294440,20014359,"Posted: 27 December, 2015",all,wrygrass,"I rate the game Shadowgate (2014) 3/5. OK...if you like that sort of thing. For me, this was a bit of a nostalgic jaunt.This is a nice little remake of the original Shadowgate mystery/puzzle game and probably would be a good game for those who miss the Myst style of gaming experience as this game requires a logic, all too often all its own, to solve the numerous puzzles of which this game is comprised. The graphics consist of mostly still or partially animated pictures which you click on with a mouse pointer while using different menu options to modify the effect of your clicks (you can also use hotkeys on the keyboard). Unlike the first iteration of Shadowgate the creators of this game have attempted to make the game feel less arbitrary and frustrating. The inclusion of multiple difficulty levels helps decrease frustration and increase replayability also. Unfortunately, this game has only 2 possible endings. 1) You die somehow and 2) You defeat the dread warlock lord and live unhappily ever after (due to the presence of an advertisement for a sequel).+Good, relatively logical puzzles (so far as this type of game is concerned).+Adequate controls for such a point-and-click style of game.+Adequate writing.+Will heavily remind you of the original without being as frustrating as the original.+Multiple difficulty levels.+No bugs.+/-Mediocre sound with adequate voice acting.-Not a great sense of mystery for such a puzzle type game.-Mediocre (at best) graphics in a odd storyboard/storybook style.-Fairly sedate music which can become repetitive over time.-The ending is severely hampered by an advertisement for a sequel.-Fairly generic story.-Some obtuse puzzles may require you to read a game walkthrough to figure them out."
